04746nam a22005415i 9780226303086DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015019941  a9780226303086  a(DE-B1597)550047  a(OCoLC)937392625  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQ175.32.V65bR57 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh1 aRiskin, Jessica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Restless Clock :bA History of the Centuries-Long Argument over What Makes Living Things Tick /cJessica Riskin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (544 p.) :b9 color plates, 51 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Huxley’s Joke, or the Problem of Agency in Nature and Science -- t1 Machines in the Garden -- t2 Descartes among the Machines -- t3 The Passive Telescope or the Restless Clock -- t4 The First Androids -- t5 The Adventures of Mr. Machine -- t6 Dilemmas of a Self- Organizing Machine -- t7 Darwin between the Machines -- t8 The Mechanical Egg and the Intelligent Egg -- t9 Outside In -- t10 History Matters -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, a scientific explanation is not meant to ascribe agency to natural phenomena: we would not say a rock falls because it seeks the center of the earth. Even for living things, in the natural sciences and often in the social sciences, the same is true. A modern botanist would not say that plants pursue sunlight. This has not always been the case, nor, perhaps, was it inevitable. Since the seventeenth century, many thinkers have made agency, in various forms, central to science. The Restless Clock examines the history of this principle, banning agency, in the life sciences. It also tells the story of dissenters embracing the opposite idea: that agency is essential to nature. The story begins with the automata of early modern Europe, as models for the new science of living things, and traces questions of science and agency through Descartes, Leibniz, Lamarck, and Darwin, among many others. Mechanist science, Jessica Riskin shows, had an associated theology: the argument from design, which found evidence for a designer in the mechanisms of nature. Rejecting such appeals to a supernatural God, the dissenters sought to naturalize agency rather than outsourcing it to a “divine engineer.” Their model cast living things not as passive but as active, self-making machines. The conflict between passive- and active-mechanist approaches maintains a subterranean life in current science, shaping debates in fields such as evolutionary biology, cognitive science, and artificial intelligence. This history promises not only to inform such debates, but also our sense of the possibilities for what it means to engage in science—and even what it means to be alive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLife (Biology) 0aLife (Biology). 0aMechanism (Philosophy) 0aMechanism (Philosophy). 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 0aVitalism. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aargument, history, historical, controversy, controversial, science, scientific, explanation, phenomena, phenomenon, nature, natural world, gravity, botany, modern, contemporary, academic, scholarly, research, interdisciplinary, 17th century, agency, life sciences, automata, descartes, leibniz, lamarck, darwin, theory, theoretical, theorist, philosopher, philosophical, machine, mechanical, technology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruy